> This tomato-y chickpea and egg bake, inspired by North African shakshuka, is
> a versatile dish that's good at any time of day. When you start your
> morning with it, it truly feels like a meal of champions. The ingredients
> are simmered until they're sultry, stewy, and saucy, then the eggs are
> plopped in and cooked using the warmth and steam from the whole mixture.
> On the side, you've got toasty flatbreads, which are perfect for scooping
> up all that deliciousness with your fingers.

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Halve, peel, and
finely chop @yellow onion{1}(peeled and finely chopped). Mince or grate
@garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Finely chop @parsley{1/4%ounce}(finely chopped).
Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%box}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a #medium pan{} over medium heat
(use an #ovenproof pan{} if you have one). Add onion and garlic. Cook,
tossing, until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in @shakshuka spice blend{1%tbsp}
and cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Add chickpeas and
@crushed tomatoes{1%box}. Stir to combine. Season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Stir 1 cup water into pan. Let simmer until thickened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Stir
in half the parsley and a pinch of @chili flakes{1%tsp} (to taste). Season
with salt and pepper. Reduce heat to medium-low.

Make two small wells in tomato mixture. Carefully crack an
@eggs{2} into each. Sprinkle salt, pepper, and @feta cheese{1/2%cup} over
everything. Transfer to oven and bake until eggs reach desired doneness,
~{5-7%minutes}.

> TIP: If your pan isn't ovenproof, continue cooking on stove, covered,
> until eggs reach desired doneness, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place @naan bread{2} (we sent more) on a #baking sheet{}. Drizzle
with olive oil, then season with salt and pepper. Toast in oven until
golden, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Sprinkle shakshuka with remaining parsley and any remaining chili flakes
(to taste). Divide between bowls and serve with flatbreads for dipping.